# Hashing Basics

**Room:** [TryHackMe – Hashing Basics](https://tryhackme.com/room/hashingbasics)
**Status:** Completed

## Summary
Covered how passwords are stored (plaintext vs. hashed), explored the
rockyou.txt wordlist used in offensive security tooling, and practiced
identifying hash algorithms using online tools.

## Key Commands
\`\`\`bash
wc -l rockyou.txt      # Count entries in the wordlist (14M+ passwords)
head rockyou.txt        # Preview top entries
\`\`\`

## Key Takeaways
- `rockyou.txt` (found at `/usr/share/wordlists/`) originates from the
  2009 RockYou data breach, where passwords were stored in plaintext
- Identified an unknown hash as MD5 using a hash-identifier tool based
  on its length and character set
- Plaintext storage and weak/reversible hashing algorithms are common
  root causes of large-scale credential breaches
